{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure can occur at the boundary between git rename detection output and CLI categorization, not only inside one pure function. REAL-INFRA: This behavior depends on real git subprocess behavior (rename detection and status format), so in-process fakes can miss command/flag/output-shape failures. MOCK-HIDE: Mocked git output could always present ideal rename records and hide real misclassification from actual git output. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: Not AI-dependent and no agent pipeline. Adversarial critique: If the tool already receives normalized change objects from an internal adapter, System may be too high and Integration could catch it. TOP2 contrast (System vs Integration): System wins because real git rename detection/CLI invocation is part of the failure boundary; it flips to Integration if behavior text explicitly guaranteed a deterministic in-process adapter contract (no subprocess parsing in scope). Rejection gate: Agentic/Workflow rejected because behavior text is about git file-status categorization only, with no model decision.","test_description":"Create a real temporary git repo, commit baseline, perform `git mv` rename, run the CLI as a subprocess, and assert the report increments only `renamed` (not `added`+`deleted`) for that path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure often appears when subprocess byte output or git binary-diff markers hit parser/decoder boundaries. REAL-INFRA: Requires real git diff behavior for binary content and real proce