r is deterministic CLI/git error-handling, not model quality.","test_description":"Create a real git repo with `git init` and no commits, execute CLI subprocess, assert zero/non-fatal exit behavior per spec and an empty structured report on stdout.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.68,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"MOCK-MISS: Accuracy depends on end-to-end interaction between history extraction, diff interpretation, and report aggregation across real repo history. REAL-INFRA: Requires real git history traversal and subprocess behavior; fake histories may not reproduce git edge semantics. MOCK-HIDE: Stubbed history payloads can pass while real command selection/range logic is wrong. LLM-DEP/MULTI-STEP: Not applicable. Adversarial critique: If this were only validating aggregator math on precomputed events, Unit/Integration would be enough. TOP2 contrast (System vs Integration): System wins because 'actual change history of the repository' implies real git history source-of-truth; it flips to Integration if behavior text limited scope to counting already-extracted events. Rejection gate: Agentic/Workflow rejected because no AI decisions or multi-agent sequencing are present.","test_description":"Construct a real repo with a known sequence of adds/deletes/renames/modifications across commits, run CLI subprocess over target range, and assert category totals equal independently computed expected counts from git ground truth.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.84,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justificatio